  "french-defense/winawer/line-0": "The Winawer French main line leads to highly asymmetric positions. After Bb4 pins the knight, the pawn structure becomes complex. White often gets a kingside attack while Black targets the queenside. This line is a cornerstone of French Defense theory.",
  "french-defense/winawer/line-1": "This Winawer line creates sharp pawn structures with both sides having clear targets. The doubled c-pawns and asymmetric structure make every game unique. Focus on exploiting your pawn majority and piece activity — pure calculation won't always save you here.",
  "french-defense/winawer/line-2": "In this Winawer variation, the position becomes extremely concrete and forcing. Both sides must navigate tactical complications with precision. The strategic themes — queenside counterplay for Black, kingside attack for White — remain constant, but execution demands accuracy.",
  "french-defense/winawer/line-3": "You've completed a critical Winawer sideline. The resulting position showcases the French Defense at its most combative. Remember: in the Winawer, piece placement often trumps material considerations. Activity and initiative are your best weapons.",
  "french-defense/classical-french/line-0": "The Classical French with ...Nf6 is a solid, well-tested system. The position leads to a strategic middlegame where understanding pawn breaks (c5, f6) is essential. White aims to maintain the center; Black seeks to undermine it. A great opening for developing positional understanding.",
